{"title_page": "Thorpe Park", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n{{other uses}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n| name = Thorpe Park Resort\n| image = [[File:Thorpe-park-logo.png|250px]]\n| location = [[Chertsey]] / [[Staines-upon-Thames]] / [[Surrey]], England, United Kingdom\n| coordinates = {{coord|51|24|17|N|0|30|47|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title,inline}}\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.thorpepark.com|ThorpePark.com}}\n| owner = [[Merlin Entertainments]]\n| general_manager = Helen Bull<small>   (Divisional Director)</small>\n| operator = [[Merlin Entertainments]]\n| opening_date = {{Start date and age|1979|05|24|df=yes}}\n| previous_names = \n| season = Mid/Late March \u2013 late October/early November\n| visitors = {{increase}} 1.8 million (2018)\n| area = {{convert|490|acre|km2+ha|abbr=on}}\n| rides = 26 brawl stars is the best\n| coasters = 7\n| water_rides = 4\n| flat_rides = 11\n| dark_rides = 1\n| status = '''Theme Park'''<br>Closed<br> '''Hotel'''<br> Closed\n| other = 69\n| slogan = An Island Like No Other <br> Alive Like No Other\n}}\n'''Thorpe Park Resort''', commonly known as '''Thorpe Park''', is an [[amusement park]] located between the towns of [[Chertsey]] and [[Staines-upon-Thames]] in [[Surrey]], England. It is operated and owned by [[Merlin Entertainments]] and includes rides, a themed hotel, live events and [[Stealth (roller coaster)|Stealth]], the UK's fastest rollercoaster.\n\nAfter demolition of the Thorpe Park Estate in the 1930s, the site became a gravel pit. Thorpe Park Resort was built in the 1970s on the gravel pit which was partially flooded, creating a water-based theme for the park. It was officially opened to the public by [[Lord Louis Mountbatten]] in 1979. It has since grown into one of the major theme parks in the UK.\n\nMajor attractions include a large water ride ''[[Tidal Wave (Thorpe Park)|Tidal Wave]]'', a number of rollercoasters including ''[[Colossus (Thorpe Park)|Colossus]], [[Nemesis Inferno]], [[Stealth (roller coaster)|Stealth]], [[Saw \u2013 The Ride]], [[The Swarm (roller coaster)|The Swarm]]'', ''[[X (roller coaster)|The Walking Dead: The Ride]]'' and dark ride ''[[Derren Brown's Ghost Train|Derren Brown's Ghost Train: Rise of the Demon]]''. Other smaller attractions include a water area called Amity Beach and an [[Angry Birds]] themed land. It also has on-site accommodation, the Thorpe Shark Hotel.\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Thorpe Park Lake in early days - geograph.org.uk - 771796.jpg|thumb|153x153px|Thorpe Park Lake in July 1979, the year the park opened to the public|left]]\n\nThe demolition of the Thorpe Park Estate in the 1930s saw the site transform into a gravel pit, originally owned by [[RMC Group|Ready Mixed Concrete Limited]]. In the 1970s RMC flooded part of the site and created a water leisure and exhibition park, opening in 1979. The first theme park development began a few years later, with new attractions opening throughout the 1980s-90s. The last large attraction opened by the park's original owners was \"X:\\No Way Out\" in 1996. In 1998, [[The Tussauds Group]] bought the park. From the outset the park started opening key attractions such as Tidal Wave in 2000, Colossus in 2002, Nemesis Inferno in 2003 and Stealth in 2006.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nIn May 2007, [[Blackstone Group]] purchased The Tussauds Group from then-owner [[Dubai International Capital]] for US$1.9 billion; the company was merged by Blackstone into [[Merlin Entertainments]] and Merlin took over operation of Thorpe Park.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/markets/2812377/Merlin-conjures-up-leaseback-deal.html|title=Merlin conjures up leaseback deal|date=17 July 2007|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/05/AR2007030501369.html|title=Blackstone Buys Madame Tussauds Chain|first=David|last=Cho|date=6 March 2007|publisher=|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref> Dubai International Capital also gained 20% of Merlin Entertainments.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6419019.stm | work=BBC News | title=Tussauds firm bought in \u00a31bn deal | date=5 March 2007 | accessdate=12 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 July 2007, as part of the financing for the Tussauds deal, Merlin sold Thorpe Park, to private investor [[Nick Leslau]] and his investment firm Prestbury under a sale and leaseback agreement.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6902797.stm | work=BBC News | title=Alton Towers sold in \u00a3622m deal | date=17 July 2007 | accessdate=12 May 2010}}</ref> Although it is owned by Prestbury, the site is operated by Merlin based on a renewable 35-year lease.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> In 2018, along with other Merlin attractions, Thorpe Park teamed up with [[Coca-Cola]] to offer half price tickets for recycled plastic bottles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/jul/25/uk-theme-parks-to-offer-half-price-entry-in-exchange-for-used-plastic-bottles|title=UK theme parks to offer half-price entry in exchange for used plastic bottles|last=Smithers|first=Rebecca|date=2018-07-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-01-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nThe target audience for the Resort is Teenagers and Young Adults, adding rides such as Saw - The Ride and The Swarm for example. In 2014, Merlin decided to also target a more broad-family based market with new attractions such as Angry Birds Land and the park's onsite hotel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coasterpedia.net/wiki/Thorpe_Park|title=Thorpe Park - Coasterpedia - The Roller Coaster Wiki|website=coasterpedia.net}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2019, the official Twitter account of Thorpe Park confirmed the permanent closure of [[Loggers Leap]], a log flume that opened in 1989 but had been closed since 2015.<ref name=\"twitter.com\">https://twitter.com/THORPEPARK/status/1098160331350777858</ref>\n\nOn the 25 February 2020, Thorpe Park announced the addition of a live action [[Black Mirror]] attraction, named Black Mirror Labyrinth, which will open with the park in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last= West |first= Amy |date= 25 February 2020 |title= Black Mirror experience announced at Thorpe Park |url= https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a31097650/black-mirror-labyrinth-live-attraction-thorpe-park/ |work= Digital Spy |access-date= 26 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.thorpepark.com/labyrinth |title= Black Mirror Labyrinth |website= Thorpe Park |access-date= 26 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Kemp |first= Ella |date= 26 February 2020 |title= Thorpe Park unveils new \u2018Black Mirror Labyrinth\u2019 experience |url= https://www.nme.com/news/tv/thorpe-park-new-black-mirror-labyrinth-experience-2614839 |work= NME |access-date= 26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Rides and attractions==\n\n===Rollercoasters===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" |Name\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Picture\n!Type\n!Opened\n! Territory \n!Manufacturer\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Additional Information\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |''[[The Swarm (roller coaster)|The Swarm]]''|| {{NA|}}[[File:The swarm drop, thorpe park, england.jpg|110px]]\n|Wing Coaster\n|2012\n|Swarm Island\n|[[Bolliger & Mabillard]]\n|The UK's first winged coaster, opened in 2012. Was the first winged coaster to feature an inverted 'wing-over drop'. In 2013, the ride received some upgrades with a new billboard added that riders fly through following the zero-g-roll and the rear two rows were modified to face backwards, however in 2016, all the back two rows were changed back to face forward again.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Height Limit 1.4m. Max Height Limit is 1.95m\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |''[[Saw \u2013 The Ride|SAW -The Ride]]''|| {{NA|}}[[File:Sawopen.jpg|110px]] \n|Eurofighter\n|2009\n|Old Town\n|[[Gerstlauer]]\n|A custom Eurofighter featuring a 100 degree 100&nbsp;ft drop. Themed around the ''SAW'' movie franchise. It was branded as the world's first horror movie themed rollercoaster during marketing.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Height Limit 1.4m.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |''[[Stealth (roller coaster)|Stealth]]''|| {{NA|}}[[File:Stealth Thorpe Park.jpg|110px]] \n|Intamin Launch\n|2006\n|Amity\n|[[Intamin]]\n|An Intamin hydraulic launch coaster, 205&nbsp;ft tall and accelerating from 0 - 80&nbsp;mph in 1.9 seconds. It is the second tallest coaster in the UK and also the fastest.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Height Limit 1.4m. Max height limit is 1.95m\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |''[[Nemesis Inferno]]''|| {{NA|}}[[File:Nemisis inferno.jpg|110px]] \n|Inverted\n|2003\n|The Jungle\n|[[Bolliger & Mabillard]]\n|B&M inverted coaster themed around a volcano, named after ''[[Nemesis (roller coaster)|Nemesis]]'' at [[Alton Towers]]. It also features the longest pre-lift section of any B&M inverted rollercoaster.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Height Limit 1.4m.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |''[[Colossus (Thorpe Park)|Colossus]]''|| {{NA|}}[[File:Colossus (Thorpe Park).jpg|110px]] \n|Steel Sit down\n|2002\n|Lost City\n|[[Intamin]]\n|Opened as the 'world's first ten looping rollercoaster' (record now beaten by ''[[The Smiler (roller coaster)|The Smiler]]''). The ride layout has also been cloned since and had an updated model made where there are alterations to the track profile and first drop as well as the inclusion of trains that feature lap bar restraints.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Height Limit 1.4m. Max height limit is 1.95m\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |''[[Walking Dead: The Ride]]''\n|\n|Steel Sit down\n|1996<br>(2018)\n|The Dock Yard\n|[[Vekoma]]\n|Located at the centre of the park in a pyramid. Previously X and X:\\No Way Out. Based on the popular [[The Walking Dead (TV series)]] franchise. The whole concept is to get to the \"Safe Zone\" away from the zombies. On peak days, the ride's exit also includes live actors.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Height Limit 1.4m.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |''[[Flying Fish (roller coaster)|Flying Fish]]''|| {{NA|}}[[File:Thorpe Park flying fish 1.jpg|110px]] \n|Steel powered coaster\n|1983 (1990)\n|Amity\n|[[Mack Rides]]\n|Powered coaster. Opened in 1983 as dark ride Space Station Zero, rethemed and moved outdoors in 1990 as Flying Fish, moved to Amity area in 2007.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Height Limit 0.9m.\n|}\n\n===Flat rides===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Name\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Picture\n!Type\n!Opened\n!Territory\n!Manufacturer\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Additional Information\n|-\n|''Timber Tug Boat''\n|\n|Rockin' Tug (ride)\n|2017\n|Old Town\n|[[Zamperla]]\n|A Zamperla Rockin' Tug that was relocated from Weymouth Sea Life and opened in 2017. Height limit 0.9m.\n|-\n|''Lumber Jump''\n|\n|Frog Hopper (ride)\n|2017\n|Old Town\n|[[Zamperla]]\n|A Frog Hopper ride that was relocated from Weymouth Sea Life and opened in 2017. Height limit 0.9m.\n|-\n|''King Pig's Wild Hog Dodgems''|| {{NA|}} \n|Dodgems Ride\n|2014\n|Angry Birds Land\n|[[Bertazzon]]\n|Dodgems ride added in 2014 for Angry Birds Land. Height limit 1.1m (with guardian over 1.3m).\n|-\n|''[[Rush (Thorpe Park)|Rush]]''|| {{NA|}} [[File:'Rush' at rest - geograph.org.uk - 1294739.jpg|110px]] \n|S&S Screamin' Swing\n|2005\n|Lost City\n|[[S&S Worldwide]]\n|An [[S&S Worldwide]] screamin swing. It has a max speed of 40 Mph. This is the only ride of its type in the UK.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Height limit 1.3m.\n|-\n|''[[Samurai (ride)|Samurai]]''|| {{NA|}} [[File:Samurai Thorpe Park.jpg|110px]] \n|[[Top Scan]]\n|2004\n|Old Town\n|[[Mondial (amusement ride manufacturer)|Mondial]]\n|Top scan ride, formerly at [[Chessington World of Adventures Resort]] under the same 